<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Drivers oppose road fee scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT faces severe public hostility to its plans to impose an extra
charge on motorists for the use of motorways, the results of an opinion poll
published today show.
The poll suggests that 86 per cent of motorists are opposed to the idea of
paying an extra charge. Of these, 65 per cent say they are paying enough in
taxes already.
Later this month the government is due to publish a green paper setting out
its plans for using motorway and trunk road charges as a means of raising
cash to fund its programme of road building.
It is understood that ministers have ruled out the possibility of installing
toll collection points on existing motorways because these would take up too
much land and slow traffic.
Instead the government seems likely to suggest that drivers wishing to use
motorways should be required to buy an annual supplementary licence fee
until electronic technology makes it possible to charge for use of the roads
on a pay-as-you-go basis.
The poll of 1,079 motorists was carried out for the Royal Automobile Club by
Research Surveys of Great Britain in March.
It shows that 37 per cent of motorists say they will use motorways less
often if charges are introduced. Nearly all of those - 97 per cent - say
they will not drive less often but use other roads instead.
This will increase fears that pay-as-you-go charges might divert traffic on
to unsuitable city streets and country lanes, with unacceptable consequences
for the environment.
The RAC said the survey showed that extra charges would only be acceptable
if they were accompanied by a package of measures that gave a fair deal to
motorists, such as more by-passes and better main roads.
</TEXT>
