<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Market depressed by state of
the economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCK prices traded in a narrow range yesterday as concern about the
state of the economy depressed market sentiment and kept many investors on
the sidelines, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 2.91 at 3,449.10,
having spent all day no more than a few points either side of Tuesday's
closing values. The more broadly based Standard&amp;Poor's 500 ended up 0.47 at
444.52, while the Amex composite finished 1.13 firmer at 425.89, and the
Nasdaq composite up 5.10 at 680.26. Trading volume on the NYSE was 272m
shares, and rises out numbered declines by 1096 to 769.
Economic concerns continued to overhang the markets. In spite of Tuesday's
stronger car sales, the bulk of the recent data has painted a picture of an
economy slowing down from the high rates of growth achieved at the end of
1992.
Yesterday's economic news came from the Federal Reserve, which released its
"Beige Book' report on the economy. It stated that there had been a modest
improvement in economic conditions recently, and that retail prices had
remained stable. There was little reaction to the report, primarily because
attention was focused on tomorrow's April employment figures, which will
give the most recent reading on condi tions in the all-important labour
market.
Dealers and investors were also keeping a close eye on developments in the
bond market, where prices traded erratically after the Treasury, as
expected, announced plans to change the mix of the government debt. In
future, the Treasury will sell 30-year bonds only twice, instead of four
times, a year. The difference will be made up with bigger sales of
shorter-dated govenment securities.
Cable television stocks, which jumped sharply on Tues day in the hope that
new federal regulations on the industry would not be as tough as originally
feared, fell yesterday amid profit-taking and after a leading brokerage
house, Gold man Sachs, made negative comments about the sector.
Time Warner fell Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 34 1/8 in volume of 1.9m shares,
Cablevision dropped Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 30 3/4 and on the Nasdaq
market, Tele-Communications fell Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 19 3/4 and Comcast
slipped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 19 3/8 .
ITT rose Dollars 3 to Dollars 83 3/4 on the news that it has entered an
agreement to sell its Dollars 2bn port folio of consumer loans to an
investment group led by Gold man Sachs. The purchase price of the deal was
not revealed.
Airline groups AMR fell Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 67 3/8 and UAL dropped
Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 133 1/2 after an analyst at Salomon Brothers
downgraded his ratings on the two stocks.
On the Nasdaq market, MCI Communications rose Dollars 1 to Dollars 48 1/8
after the company won an Dollars 80m global services con tract from banking
group JP Morgan.
Canada
TORONTO shrugged off early losses and a sell-off in New York to post
moderate gains in heavy trade. The TSE-300 closed up 7.64 points to 3,786.81
on turnover of 58.54m valued at CDollars 595.84m. Advances led declines 373
to 328.
The Consumer products and communications sectors gained favour as investors
move to expand portfolios. Consumer products were up 67.36 or 1.04 per cent,
to 6,521.47.
</TEXT>
