<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / UK Company News: National Express makes purchase and
disposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL EXPRESS, the coach service operator which was floated on the Stock
Exchange in December, is acquiring Scottish Citylink Coaches, the main
subsidiary of Saltire Holdings, for Pounds 5.11m in shares, loan notes and
cash.
At the same time the group announced that it has agreed to sell Express
Travel, its coach operating subsidiary, and Bruce's Coaches, a coach
operating subsidiary acquired with Scottish Citylink, for Pounds 1.2m in
cash to British Bus.
The sale of Express Travel represents a further step in reducing NEL's
involvement in the actual operation of coaches. Express Travel, which will
continue to provide coaches under contract to NEL, made profits of Pounds
537,000 and had net tangible assets of Pounds 942,000 at the end of
December.
Scottish Citylink organises and markets 16 long distance scheduled coach
services in Scotland, together with a number of commuter services including
the Glasgow/Edinburgh link, and 10 cross-border routes between Scotland and
London. It also offers services to Ireland and markets services between
Scotland and mainland Europe.
National said the acquisition would help it compete more effectively on
cross-border routes with British Rail, significantly broaden its customer
base and geographic spread and enhance profitability through the addition of
Scottish Citylink's higher margin services within Scotland.
Under the terms of the deal, Saltire's shareholders will receive 1.8m new
National Express shares with the balance of Pounds 1.8m to be satisfied in
loan notes, up to a maximum of Pounds 1.5m, and cash.
National's shares closed 1p up at 187p yesterday.
</TEXT>
