<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Asil Nadir Flees to Cyprus: SFO stuck with no trial and only
token gestures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE TRIAL of Mr Asil Nadir
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
one of the most high-profile prosecutions brought by the Serious Fraud
Office - was due to start on September 13. He faced 13 charges alleging he
stole Pounds 34m from Polly Peck. There is now no chance that the trial will
take place.
With Mr Nadir beyond reach in northern Cyprus, the SFO can do little except
make token gestures. In a short statement yesterday, it said it was
considering further action, including issuing a fresh warrant for his
arrest. Police were also investigating how he was able to slip out of the
country in a private jet. Both courses of action, however, remain academic.
Unless Mr Nadir returns voluntarily, the papers for his prosecution will
gather dust.
The SFO is left to decide whether to go ahead with the prosecution of Mr
Nadir's co-defendant, Mr John Turner, Polly Peck's chief accountant. He
faces two charges of false accounting which he denies. He could stand trial
on his own. Yesterday, the SFO said only that it was too early to consider
its position on Mr Turner's case.
Mr Nadir was first arrested at Heathrow Airport in December 1990 on his
return from a trip to Turkey. He was initially charged with 18 counts of
theft and false accounting involving Pounds 25m. As the investigation
proceeded, the charges mounted until he faced 66 charges involving almost
Pounds 120m.
However, in June 1992, Mr Justice Tucker, the trial judge, ordered the
dismissal of 46 of the charges, These referred to money transfers from Polly
Peck to Unipac, a subsidiary.
The charges were later trimmed again to the current 13 which formed the
final indictment on which he would be tried. Mr Nadir always protested his
innocence and maintained that proof of this could be found in northern
Cyprus. The fact the SFO had never considered it necessary to visit there
angered him deeply.
As the case continued, Mr Nadir's health broke. He suffered from a severe
depression which left him unable to instruct his solicitor for several weeks
and having to seek psychiatric help.
</TEXT>
