<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Swiss Bank tops BZW's cash offer for scrip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SWISS Bank Corporation has made a late intervention in BAT's enhanced scrip
dividend scheme, by offering shareholders a higher cash alternative than
BZW.
Under the scheme, formulated by BZW, BAT shareholders were offered a scrip
dividend of 33.9p per share, a 50 per cent premium to the cash dividend of
22.6p announced on March 10.
BZW said that shareholders who wanted cash could take a cash alternative to
the enhanced scrip of 32.2p, free of dealing costs - a 5 per cent discount
to cover the joint broker's risk in underwriting the deal.
Now SBC has said it will offer shareholders a cash alternative of 33.22p per
scrip share, free of dealing costs - a discount of only 2 per cent.
BAT said its attitude to the SBC offer was 'strictly neutral', adding: 'If
they want to make an offer, that is their affair. Our only concern would be
if any confusion arose so late in the timetable.'
BAT shareholders must communicate their decision on the scrip by Tuesday,
and last night nearly 38 per cent of the group's 150,000 shareholders had
already made irrevocable elections.
BZW claimed that SBC's late entry into the process and targeted method of
advertising it - through an advertisement in today's Financial Times -
suggested that SBC was more interested in 'creaming off' institutional
investors, rather than small shareholders.
SBC denied that, and said it had started looking at the scheme because a
large number of its own clients were BAT shareholders. Depending on market
reaction, to this offer, it would consider making similar offers for scrip
of other companies which followed BAT's example.
SBC discussed aspects of the scheme with the Stock Exchange, but its offer
is conditional on approval being granted by the council of the exchange.
The enhanced scrip offered by RTZ Corporation, the mining group which became
the second company to follow BAT's example, was accepted by holders of 89
per cent of the group's shares - more than expected. Only 19 per cent of
those took BZW's cash alternative.
</TEXT>
