<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Royal Insurance makes Pounds 404m cash call
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL Insurance yesterday surprised the markets with a deeply discounted
one-for-three Pounds 404m rights issue which should enable it to take
advantage of recent rises in insurance rates in the UK and overseas,
News that the group returned to the black in the first quarter, however,
helped calm unease among investors with the shares falling only 9p yesterday
to close at 307p, compared with the rights issue price of 255p.
Pre-tax profits in the first quarter of 1993 amounted to Pounds 2m compared
with a Pounds 48m loss during the same period last year. Royal lost Pounds
679m between 1990 and 1992
'We felt the time was right to take advantage of the market upturn,' said Mr
Richard Gamble, chief executive, who said: 'We have trimmed back
sufficiently and want to maintain the market share that we have. We are not
looking to make any rapid expansion but the capital will support the whole
base of our business.'
The issue has been underwritten by Lazard Brothers and Barings. Brokers to
the issue are SG Warburg Securities and Hoare Govett Corporate Finance. And
the proceeds will be invested directly in Royal's general insurance
business, increasing its solvency by 11 per cent to approximately 54 per
cent.
Although several insurers have raised cash through subordinated bond and
debt issues, Royal is only the second composite insurer to ask its
shareholders for fresh capital. Commercial Union raised Pounds 428m in
February.
'We understand the reasons why they have done it but we are disappointed,'
said Mr David Hudson, analyst with Credit Lyonnais Laing. 'It dilutes the
potential earnings recovery. Without the rights issue the balance sheet
would look a little bit wobbly.'
Royal's first-quarter figures indicate continuing improvement in
underwriting results, especially in the UK where underwriting losses fell to
Pounds 21m compared with Pounds 91m at the same stage last year. Rises in
premium rates, milder weather and a fall in mortgage indemnity losses were
responsible. Underwriting losses in the United States rose to Pounds 65m
(from Pounds 41m).
The new cash could help Royal expand in some markets. Mr Roy Elms,
underwriting director, said opportunities in the commercial risks market
were particularly attractive.
The withdrawal of reinsurance capacity in recent months had lead to a
reduction in competition in this sector.
Royal Global, the subsidiary which specialises in insuring the risks of
multinational companies, has been hampered by its poor security ratings in
the past and should benefit from the injection.
'It will enhance their position when they can say they are part of a company
with a 50 per cent solvency rating,' added Mr Gamble.
Further expansion is also on the cards at The Insurance Service (TIS), the
Gloucester-based 'direct' motor insurer. By contrast sales through brokers,
which generate two-thirds of Royal's motor business, remained static.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
