<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / CBI chief calls for changes in financing of small businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry,
yesterday outlined a six-point plan to change the way small businesses are
financed in Britain.
He said urgent action was needed to reduce the casualty rate from cash-flow
problems as the economy recovered from recession.
Mr Davies said clearing banks, which in the 1980s overlent to small
businesses, were now in danger of making as big a mistake by overtightening
their lending rules.
'We ought to be trying to move faster towards a more flexible form of small
business finance,' he told northern members of the British Venture Capital
Association in Manchester.
His proposals are to form the basis for developing a more formal CBI policy
in the next few weeks.
The points were:
Speed up payment of money owing to small businesses by big companies and the
public sector, often the worst offender. Mr Davies said all companies and
public bodies should follow the CBI's code of conduct, which encouraged
prompt payment.
Wider use of factoring, where companies sell their invoices to finance
houses, often subsidiaries of banks, which then collect the money. 'The
attraction is that it would force banks to take a more direct interest in
small businesses and to understand the strength of their customer base,' Mr
Davies added.
Banks should be more willing to swap debt for equity.
The venture capital industry should look at its investment pattern, in which
64 per cent of funds go into management buy-outs, only 4 per cent into
start-ups, 3 per cent into early stage funding and 4 per cent into
refinancing bank debt. These last three categories needed a bigger share of
money available, he said.
A replacement for the Business Expansion Scheme which, Mr Davies said, had
acted as a middle-class tax-shelter and had been abused, with funds going to
ventures such as wine cellars. It should apply only to investment in a new
type of local investment company, through which small business 'angels'
could take stakes in targeted ventures. A successor to the Unlisted
Securities Market, which the stock exchange wants to abolish but has
temporarily reprieved while alternatives are considered.
Mr Davies said there had to be an easier way of going public than the
costlier route of obtaining a full listing. Something like the USM was
needed to assist quick and easy exits for equity stakeholders in successful
small businesses.
He also called for wider tax relief on investments in growing businesses
where realised profits were reinvested in other new unquoted businesses - a
Budget proposal watered down in the Finance Bill.
</TEXT>
