<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Government's school tests hit by second resignation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT plans for school tests for 14-year-olds suffered another setback
yesterday when a second adviser resigned from the council drawing up the
tests.
Dr John Marenbon decided to leave the Schools Examinations and Assessment
Council after a disagreement over assessing schoolchildren's understanding
of English.
His departure follows the resignation of Lord Skidelsky on Tuesday in
protest at the government's handling of its review of the national
curriculum.
In his resignation letter, Dr Marenbon, who chaired the council's English
committee, described the tests, which two teachers' unions are boycotting,
as 'inadequate and unfair'.
He said: 'I have made repeated requests that this paper be postponed and
carefully rewritten.' Dr Marenbon is fellow of English at Trinity College,
Cambridge, and a leading supporter of the national curriculum's proposed new
emphasis on traditional 'classic' works.
He described the timetable for the tests as 'impossible', and told Mr Patten
that many of his advisers were 'too keen to tell you what they believe you
want to hear'.
Mr Patten said he was 'extremely surprised and sorry' to receive Dr
Marenbon's resignation. However, he said the tests should go ahead as it
would be the last chance for 14-year-olds to be assessed before sitting
their GCSE examinations.
The SEAC also reacted with anger, saying it had not disregarded Dr
Marenbon's advice. It said the tests had been drawn up to Mr Patten's
specification and that 'leading Shakespearean scholars' had been consulted.
It said: 'Dr Marenbon's views on these tests, though valuable, have to be
set against those of other experts.'
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters Union of Women Teachers, which is boycotting the tests, said:
'The whole exercise is in complete disarray.'
Ms Ann Taylor, Labour's education spokesman, said: 'This second resignation
in two days shows how isolated the secretary of state has become. Now we
learn that he does not even listen to his own hand-picked advisers.'
</TEXT>
