<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Telelvison
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Not all Japanese eat whalemeat. In Whale Wars (BBC 2, 9.35), Japanese
conservationists express their opposition ahead of next week's meeting of
the International Whaling Commission. It also emerges that the waters have
been muddied by the whaling industry's effort to convince the Japanese that
the western campaign against whaling is an assault on their cultural
identity.
A thousand brains must have considered the idea of a TV pastiche of Radio
4's eternal Desert Island Discs, only to reject it. Now someone has come up
with Memento (C4, 8.00), a misconceived, feeble series. However, anyone who
cannot have enough of the creamy timbre of Dame Kiri Te Kanawa's voice can
enjoy her performance tonight, enthusing about her eight most prized
possessions. There is a lot wrong with the British legal system, yet it is
still all to the good that TV cameras are held at bay while cases are
decided. They do it differently in Luxembourg, which made possible tonight's
episode of True Stories: Lovers on Trial (C4, 9.35), a gory murder story
worthy of Zola.
</TEXT>
