<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Drivers oppose road fee scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT faces severe public hostility to its plans to impose an extra
charge on motorists for the use of motorways, the results of an opinion poll
published today show.
The poll suggests that 86 per cent of motorists are opposed to the idea of
paying an extra charge.
Later this month the government is due to publish a green paper on its plans
for using motorway and trunk road charges as a means of funding its
road-building programme. The government seems likely to suggest that drivers
wishing to use motorways should be required to pay an annual supplementary
licence fee.
The poll of 1,079 motorists was carried out for the Royal Automobile Club by
Research Surveys of Great Britain in March.
It shows that 37 per cent of motorists say they will use motorways less
often if charges are introduced.
</TEXT>
