<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / ECGD gave Matrix cover for Iraq deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EXPORT Credit Guarantee Department agreed to provide cover for about
Pounds 6.5m of equipment destined for Baghdad which it suspected of being
used for military uses, the arms-for-Iraq inquiry heard yesterday.
The cover was provided in 1989 after the department thought it had been
given approval by other government departments.
Mr David Bryars, chief underwriter for the department's short-term credit
operations at the time, said concern about the equipment being exported by
Matrix Churchill, the Midlands-based machine-tool manufacturer, through
Industrias Cardoen of Chile, led him to contact the Foreign Office for
advice.
According to confidential Whitehall documents released during the trial of
three former Matrix Churchill directors last year, the exchange took place
in January 1989.
The department, which underwrites loans for export contracts, was then
government-owned. It has since been partly privatised.
Yesterday Mr Bryars, questioned by Miss Presiley Baxendale QC, counsel for
the investigation, said a Foreign Office official told him that Matrix
Churchill's goods were the subject of an investigation by the Foreign Office
and the Department of Trade and Industry, and that the matter of whether or
not the equipment should be licensed was with ministers.
'He said that his feeling was the decision would be that an export licence
would not be required . . . I was given a strong impression that it would be
OK,' Mr Bryars said. A similar impression, he added, was given by Customs
and Excise.
He was giving evidence on the second day of the public hearings conducted by
Lord Justice Scott into the extent to which the government may have colluded
in the export of defence sales to Iraq in breach of guidelines and
export-licensing arrangements. The inquiry continues on Monday.
</TEXT>
