<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Directors want company law changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANY LAW should be amended to reflect modern trends in corporate
governance, according to a Mori survey of senior directors published
yesterday.
More than four fifths would approve of amendments to require listed
companies to establish a remuneration committee to approve executives' pay,
wholly or mainly comprised of non-executives.
Three quarters would support a change in the law to oblige listed companies
to establish audit committees of non-executive directors responsible for
liaising with auditors.
The findings come in a poll of 200 chief executives and non-executive
directors commissioned by executive search companies Executive Interim
Management and Egon Zehnder International.
More than 90 per cent of non-executives and 87 per cent of chief executives
agreed that the law should be changed to require companies to disclose the
salary and performance-related emoluments of the chairman and highest-paid
director.
Nearly a third said no such remuneration committee existed in their own
company. Half did not have a non-executive audit committee with the proposed
powers.
Two thirds approved of the Cadbury report, which includes a code of best
practice to which companies will have to refer in annual reports from this
summer under Stock Exchange rules.
But two thirds disagreed with nominations committees with a majority of
non-executive directors to select future appointments.
Two thirds of non-executives said they were approached personally by the
chairman and a quarter already knew the chairman or chief executive.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
