<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Council patrol aims to cut crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NORTH-EAST local authority is setting up a street patrol to try to reduce
crime on housing estates. It is believed to be the first such patrol in
Britain to be run by a council.
The 'community force', approved this week by Sedgefield District Council's
policy and resources committee, will comprise 11 uniformed officials on
patrol.
Under the scheme, they will report by radio to a control depot which will
alert police to crime. The force will also consult residents on social
problems, liaise with police and other groups, call on vulnerable
householders and advise on crime prevention.
The service, expected to cost Pounds 220,000 in its first year and Pounds
180,000 a year thereafter, will be funded by the council. It has been
favourably received by Durham police.
But the Police Federation said the community force was a sad comment on
government underfunding of the police.
</TEXT>
