<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour ready for union offensive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUPPORT within the Labour party for the proposals loosening the party's
links with the unions is to be mobilised shortly in a counter-attack to the
campaign against the reforms mounted by some of the largest unions.
Since February, when Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, threw his weight
behind the plans to end the unions' ability to vote in the selection of
parliamentary candidates and in the election of leader and deputy leader,
some of the biggest unions have been vigorously opposing the move.
At least some of the biggest unions will need to be won over, as the unions
will still account for 70 per cent of the total vote when the issue is
discussed at the party's annual conference in October.
The basis of the decision will be a recommendation from the ruling National
Executive Committee, which will be drawn up in July, after the present
consultation period is over.
The counter-attack is intended to shame the unions into not using their
block votes to kill the reforms. It will highlight the extent of support for
the changes within the constituency parties as well as among Labour MPs, and
underline the weapon that would be handed to the Tories if the reforms were
defeated.
Most prominent in the campaign against the loosening of the links have been
the Transport and General Workers Union, the GMB general union, and the
National Union of Public Employees. But late last month Usdaw, the
shopworkers' union, voted narrowly to retain a union vote in the selection
of Labour parliamentary candidates, against the recommendation of the
union's executive.
Mr Bryan Gould, a former shadow minister and candidate for the Labour
leadership, last night accused the party of failing to land a blow on the
Tories 'through the worst recession for two generations' in the influential
left-of-centre paper Tribune.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8631 Labor Organizations.
    P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
