<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Mixed views greet amendment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Page 1, line 18 (clause 1), after 'Community', insert 'with the exception of
the Protocol on Social Policy on page 117 of Cm 1934'.
Amendment 2 to the
European Communities
(Amendment) Bill.
DEPENDING on who is asked, Labour's briefly worded 'amendment two' - as
accepted by the government yesterday - could throw a legislative spanner
into the Maastricht bill, halting British ratification. Or it will force the
government to sign up for the social chapter. Or it can simply be flung
aside as ratification moves ever closer.
The immediate consequence is that the protocol on the social chapter agreed
at Maastricht, which included an opt-out for Britain, will not be part of
the legislation approved by the Commons. But the effect that this will then
have is far from clear.
EURO-SCEPTICS argue the amendment means legislation approved by parliament
could prove insufficient for the government to sign the Maastricht treaty.
Confusion has thus been created. They will seek a 'judicial review' of
ministers' use of the royal prerogative - the formal mechanism used to sign
treaties.
Specifically, Tory Euro-sceptics believe the government will not have the
power to contribute to the administrative costs of the social chapter, which
the government will probably help pay in spite of supposedly having opted
out.
THE GOVERNMENT argues that, even though the protocol will be excluded from
domestic law, it still stands in the treaty. Britain can ratify the treaty
because the protocol imposed no burdens on the country that required
domestic legislation. The social chapter opt-out remains.
Incorporation of the protocol into UK law was 'desirable' for the sake of
neatness but not 'essential,' Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, told
MPs yesterday.
Financial costs to Britain of administering the social chapter are
insignificant and can probably be charged to the Treasury's 'consolidated
fund' under the European Communities Act 1972, ministers believe.
LABOUR agrees broadly with the government that ratification has not been
stopped. But Mr George Robertson, Europe spokesman, says a 'series of
minefields' have been created that can only be solved by accepting the
social chapter.
There could be a case for judicial review on ratification; certainly there
is now moral pressure on the government to accept the social chapter. There
might also be challenges in the European Court of Justice by British workers
who - now the opt-out is removed from UK law - demand that the social
chapter's provisions should apply to them.
Separately, Liberal Democrats, who also back the social chapter, argue that
extra powers for the European Parliament have to be agreed by the Commons.
The effect of the amendment is to override that principle - offering a fresh
avenue for a legal challenge.
</TEXT>
