<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Tecs offer ways to cut jobless tally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUNDREDS of ways to reduce unemployment, including re-skilling up to 400
workers to decommission Soviet nuclear submarines, have been submitted to
the government by Training and Enterprise Councils.
Tecs, which administer state-funded training schemes for the jobless, were
invited by the government to compete for an extra Pounds 21m to run projects
to cut unemployment in the present financial year.
The deadline for appli-cations was yesterday. Tecs have taken a variety of
approaches. Birmingham Tec has looked for a closer working relationship
between itself and the Employment Service, which runs non-training options
such as Jobclubs. It wants to offer employers a single 'gateway' for
recruitment.
Aztec in south-west London has submitted two proposals. The first proposes
an allowance of up to Pounds 75 a week to help jobless people with the
transition from benefits to a work pattern involving a number of part-time
jobs. It also suggests training grants for employers to support recruitment
of the long-term unemployed.
Cumbria Tec is submitting a project whereby former VSEL shipyard workers,
employed by a newly created marine technology transfer company, would be
trained to decommission Soviet submarines. An initial 10 people would be
retrained, with possibilities for up to 400 being involved in the long term.
Ideas had to be new, they had to be capable of being set up by September and
of making a significant contribution to reducing unemployment. The
government expects to fund between 12 and 24 projects.
Many Tecs, while applying for the extra funding, have been critical of the
scheme known as Tec Challenge. One critic said worthwhile schemes take more
than a few months to set up and 'Tecs are not interested in short-term
wheezes that are intended to massage the government's unemployment
register'.
The government yesterday placed more small companies outside the scope of
the industry training levy.
In future companies with combined payroll and payments to labour-only
sub-contractors of less than Pounds 61,000 a year will not be subject to the
levy. The previous ceiling was Pounds 45,000.
</TEXT>
