<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Consumer interest points to recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMER INTEREST in buying goods and services has shown a big increase
since the beginning of the year, although it stabilised between February and
March, a business information company said yesterday.
The levelling off in enthusiasm for purchases shown by an index compiled by
NTC Research adds to fears that the recovery may be weak.
The index, taking in TV advertising, job vacancies, share prices, interest
rates and retail sales, leapt from 114.23 in January to 127.76 in February.
In March it moved up only fractionally to 127.89.
Vodafone, the Newbury-based mobile telephone company, yesterday added to
evidence that the recovery is under way by reporting that April was its best
month for three years.
The company added a net 18,766 subscribers to its network in April - the
largest number of new subscribers since May 1990 - bringing total
subscribers to 856,000.
A year ago the monthly tally for new subscribers was running at about 5,000
net.
Figures for new connections by cable TV companies offering phone services
also show strong growth.
According to the Independent Television Commission, the first three months
of the year saw an increase of a third in the number of residential and
business lines, taking the total number of exchange lines installed to
143,660.
Meanwhile the UK's electronics industry is seeing signs of recovery after
two years of stagnant sales. Mr Cyril Teed, president of the EEA electronics
industry trade association, said last night at its annual dinner that new
orders rose by 7 per cent last year and were back at 1989 levels.
NTC Research, Farm Road, Henley-on-Thames, Oxfordshire, RG9 1EJ.
