<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Aid signalled for private landlords
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT may have to provide further assistance to encourage private
landlords to increase their presence in the housing market, the prime
minister said yesterday.
Speaking at the Harry Simpson Memorial lecture in London, Mr Major said:
'There is clearly a need for a larger private-rented sector in Britain. We
have released some of the old shackles on landlords. But we may need to go
further if the sector is to show any significant growth.'
Ministers have been contemplating incentives to revive the private-rented
sector but this is the first time, according to officials, that the prime
minister has signalled the possibility of providing further assistance to
landlords.
Sir George Young, the housing minister, in particular is thought to be keen
to reinvigorate private renting which at the turn of the century provided
about 90 per cent of housing compared with less than 7.5 per cent by 1990.
He yesterday welcomed the prime minister's comments, which he said
underlined the government's commitment to private renting.
The Treasury is also thought to be receptive to moves to encourage private
renting which could improve the supply of housing without restarting an
inflationary rise in house prices.
Private renting previously has been encouraged by the 1988 Housing Act which
restricted tenants' rights and gave landlords greater freedom to set rents.
An extension of the Business Expansion Scheme also provided tax breaks for
investors in housing for rent. The scheme finishes at the end of this year.
Mr Major said, however, that the great majority of people still wanted to
own their own home. He was pleased by recent signs that stability was
returning to the housing market but he did not want to see a return to a
'frenetic market with prices rising dramatically'. This would be
inappropriate for the housing market and the economy, he added.
</TEXT>
