<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Sharp rise in subscribers to Vodafone
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VODAFONE, the Newbury-based mobile telephone company, yesterday reported
April as its best month for three years, further evidence from business that
the recovery is under way.
Vodafone added a net 18,766 subscribers to its network in April, its best
month for new subscribers since May 1990. The total number of subscribers is
now 856,000.
A year ago the monthly tally for new subscribers was running at about 5,000
net.
The number of customers cancelling their subscriptions has also continued to
decline and is down to about one for every five new customers.
For the first time since Vodafone introduced its low-user tariff - called
LowCall - last October, the number of new subscribers opting for the full
business tariff exceeded the number of new LowCall connections.
Mr Gerry Whent, chief executive, attributed the growth to 'the combination
of support from the independent service providers, our marketing initiatives
and the undisputed quality of the Vodafone network'.
Figures for new connections by cable TV companies offering phone services
also show strong growth in recent months.
According to the Independent Television Commission, the first three months
of the year saw an increase of a third in the number of residential and
business lines, taking the total number of exchange lines installed to
143,660. The UK's electronics industry is seeing signs of recovery after two
years of stagnant sales, Mr Cyril Teed, president of EEA, the electronics
industry trade association, said last night. Speaking at the association's
annual dinner he said new orders rose by 7 per cent last year and were now
back at 1989 levels.
