<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Sunday trading 'endangers 19,000 jobs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNRESTRICTED Sunday shopping would lower retail prices and raise
shopworkers' average wages but lead to the loss of 19,000 jobs in the retail
sector, according to an independent study commissioned by the Home Office.
It says tighter restrictions, favoured by unions, small shops and religious
groups, would create some jobs. But industry efficiency would suffer, retail
prices would rise and average wages would fall.
The study says about 40 per cent of shops currently open on Sunday in
England and Wales, when about 6 per cent of weekly shopping is done. But it
finds the trend has not perceptibly increased total retail sales and doubts
they would rise even if Sunday trading were wholly deregulated.
However, the study, which uses an economic model based on data supplied by
retailers, finds that the various options for changing the law now being
considered in Westminster would have widely differing effects on retailing
costs, employment levels and patterns of shopping.
The study was published as 245 MPs from all the main parties signed a
parliamentary early-day motion yesterday urging the government to support a
private member's bill which calls for stricter curbs on Sunday trading.
The motion noted that the bill - introduced by Mr Ray Powell, the Labour MP
for Ogmore, and backed by the Keep Sunday Special campaign - had been
amended in committee to allow Sunday opening by DIY outlets, garden centres
and convenience stores of up to 3,000 sq ft.
The study says that total deregulation - one of the options favoured by the
government - would cut retail prices by 0.3 per cent, saving the average
household Pounds 18.40 on its annual shopping bill.
But because the overall volume of trade would remain about the same, shops
would have to be more competitive to cover opening for an extra day. That
would would lead to some retailers going out of business and about 19,000
jobs disappearing, the report said.
The study, by the London Economics consultancy, forecasts that almost
two-thirds of shops in England and Wales would trade on Sunday if it were
made legal. It does not cost the amended version of Mr Powell's bill, but it
says that in its original, more restrictive, form, the bill would have added
0.4 per cent to retail prices, costing the average household Pounds 25.80 a
year.
The original bill would have created 22,500 retailing jobs, but cut the
average wage by Pounds 172 a year. It would also have led to expanded
retailing capacity.
The Shopping Hours Reform Council welcomed the study as a victory for
consumers, and said it supported its own proposals for partial deregulation.
But John Lewis Partnership, which does not open on Sundays, called it
'highly slanted'.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, commissioned the study last year
after offering parliament three options for Sunday trading reform. These
range from the present curbs to total deregulation.
The government's bill is expected to be included in the legislative
timetable for the next parliamentary session. Mr Powell's bill reaches the
Commons report stage later this month, but is thought unlikely to survive.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                      WHAT THE PROPOSALS WILL MEAN
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                    Powell Bill   Powell Bill   RSAR   SHRC     Full
                      (tight)      (liberal)                Deregulation
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
CHANGE IN RETAIL EMPLOYMENT
  Medium term             -900      -1,000     -2,100   +900     +1,400
  Long term            +22,500     +21,000    +12,900 -5,300    -19,100
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
LONG-TERM CHANGE IN WAGES
                        Pounds      Pounds     Pounds  Pounds    Pounds
  Annual total             28m         24m       -16m     7m       45m
  Per employee            -172        -167       -125     51       135
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
COST TO HOUSEHOLDS      Pounds      Pounds     Pounds  Pounds    Pounds
  Per household          25.80       23.60      15.70    6.70    -18.40
                       Percent     Percent    Percent  Percent   Percent
  of retail prices         0.4         0.4        0.3    -0.1       0.3
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: London Economics
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
