<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Fall in pound rebounds on holiday costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEVALUATION of sterling yesterday hit the package holiday industry with
Thomson, Britain's largest travel company, blaming the weaker pound for
price increases of up to 10 per cent on holidays to some European ski
resorts.
Prices for all 1993-94 winter holidays sold by Thomson will, however,
increase by only 2 per cent after the company warned resorts they risked
losing UK business.
Thomson's winter programme, which goes on sale on Friday, provides the first
indication of how sterling's fall will affect big tour operators' prices.
This summer's holidays are unaffected by last September's devaluation
because tour operators had bought forward their foreign currency until next
October.
Ms Rosemary Astles, Thomson's marketing director, said price rises for
skiing holidays in France, Austria and Switzerland had been unavoidable.
Thomson has, however, increased its ski programmes in Spain and Italy, where
weaker local currencies have enabled the company to lower prices on some
programmes. Ms Astles said the price of skiing holidays in Italy had fallen
by 5 per cent overall. France, Austria and Switzerland account for 75 per
cent to 80 per cent of Thomson's ski programme for 1993-94 compared with 85
per cent last winter.
The prices of winter holidays in Florida have gone up by only 3 per cent, in
spite of sterling's weakness against the dollar. Ms Astles said Thomson had
been able to keep prices low because the US recession and the reluctance of
Americans to travel had caused an oversupply of Florida holiday
accommodation.
Thomson had warned all resorts they would not attract UK tourists unless
they took the weaker pound into account when setting prices. Ms Astles said:
'Our negotiating stance was to say: 'If you don't help us you will lose
business.' Not everybody helped us, but quite a lot of people realised that
it's no use having a price rise of 14 per cent.'
Thomson said sales of winter 1993-94 holidays through travel agents were
likely to be slightly up on last winter's 2.7m. UK and US government
negotiators yesterday began a new round of talks in London to attempt to
negotiate a new 'open skies' aviation agreement between the two countries.
The talks are expected to take several months.
</TEXT>
