<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Hoover accused of confusing workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOOVER, the domestic appliances manufacturer, was accused yesterday by the
AEEU union of contradicting itself over the future of its British
operations.
Mr Jimmy Airlie, the engineering and electrical union's Scottish chief
executive officer, said he had written to Mr Leonard Hadley, president and
chief executive of Maytag, the US parent company, asking him who was running
Hoover.
Earlier this year Mr Airlie negotiated an efficiency deal with Hoover that
resulted in its decision to transfer vacuum cleaner production from Dijon in
France to Scotland.
Last week doubt was cast over that agreement when it became clear that the
company is reviewing all its European operations.
Mr Airlie said yesterday that Mr Hadley and the company's new European
president, Mr Gerald Kamman, appeared to have contradicted each other over
the future of Hoover's Scottish plant at Cambuslang.
In his annual statement to shareholders in Iowa on April 27 Mr Hadley said
the move from Dijon to Cambuslang was proceeding as planned.
'We took a 1992 charge of Dollars 53m to cover the expenses of this European
reorganisation, but we expect to recover those charges in the future as we
will eliminate duplicate overheads, reduce labour costs and realise
economies of scale', he added.
Only a day earlier Mr Kamman wrote to every Hoover employee in Europe to say
that owing to financial losses 'nothing will escape review', including the
transfer of production from Dijon to Scotland.
Hoover was unavailable for comment yesterday.
Management, Page 8
</TEXT>
