<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Arabs agree to more peace talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ARAB delegations yesterday agreed to continue talks with Israel until the
end of next week, encouraged by the prospect of a meeting with US President
Bill Clinton. Syria had earlier warned it would consider breaking off the
current ninth round of talks on Friday, unless there were better prospects
of progress.
The White House has not yet confirmed that Mr Clinton will receive the
delegations, but a senior Arab diplomat said yesterday that the symbolic
significance of the US president becoming directly involved for the first
time since the process opened in October 1991 was enough to ensure the
delegations remained in Washington.
Mrs Hanan Ashrawi, spokeswoman for the Palestinian delegation, warned
however that continued Israeli violence against Palestinians in the occupied
territories was damaging the atmosphere at the negotiations. She said that
the killing of eight Palestinians during the previous 48 hours had caused a
visible deterioration in relations.
Mrs Ashrawi added she was also disappointed Israel had not yet announced the
names of further Palestinian deportees who would be allowed to return to
their homes. 'Israeli intentions must be judged by what they do on the
ground, as much as by what happens in the negotiations,' she said.
</TEXT>
