<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 93 / Serbs seek to impose conditions on Bosnian peace plan: You
cannot oppose and fight the entire world, warns Greek premier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, LAURA SILBER and LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PALE, MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOSNIAN Serb assembly was last night moving towards the adoption of a
document listing nine conditions for the acceptance of the international
peace plan on Bosnia.
A vote for such a document would almost certainly be viewed by the US and
its western allies as a rejection of the plan, brokered by Mr Cyrus Vance
and Lord Owen, the UN and European Community mediators.
As the 82 deputies of the self-styled parliament continued their debate into
the early hours of the morning, President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia and
President Dobrica Cosic of the rump Yugoslavia made a dramatic appeal to the
deputies to adopt the plan without qualifications. 'We can't help you any
more,' they said, warning that the assembly's intended action would provoke
military intervention.
Mr Constantine Mitsotakis, prime minister of Greece, a traditional ally of
Orthodox Serbia, warned the delegates: 'You cannot oppose and fight the
entire world.'
Mr Dragan Kalinic, health minister of the self-proclaimed Serb Republic in
Bosnia, said the parliament meeting in the mountain stronghold of Pale near
Sarajevo, 'would vote 'yes' to the plan but with conditions'.
These were contained in a draft document to be voted on by the assembly and
included the abolition of international sanctions against Yugoslavia within
three weeks as well as changes in the Vance-Owen map which would link Serb
provinces of Bosnia.
At the vital session of the Bosnian Serb parliament, bitter divisions
emerged over whether to accept the plan or reject it and face possible
punitive air strikes from the US and its allies.
Diplomatic observers believed that most of the Bosnian Serb conditions, if
confirmed, would be rejected by the international community. The US, Britain
and France have all stressed that sanctions must remain in place until it
was absolutely clear that the Bosnian Serbs were implementing the peace plan
as agreed.
Moreover, the international mediators, who have proposed dividing Bosnia
into 10 semi-autonomous provinces, have always been careful to avoid drawing
a map which would enable the Bosnian Serbs to consolidate their territory
and declare a separate state. The Bosnian Serbs, on the other hand, have
never concealed their long-term aim of subsuming such a state in a Greater
Serbia.
Other conditions contained in the document included a land swap with the
Croats, the right of Serb minorities in Croat and Moslem provinces to vote
on whether they should join neighbouring Serb provinces, and the provision
that 50 per cent of UN troops deployed along confrontation lines come from
Orthodox countries.
Meanwhile, the US and Russia yesterday glossed over their differences on
Bosnia to present a united front after talks in Moscow between Mr Warren
Christopher, the US secretary of state, and Mr Andrei Kozyrev, his Russian
opposite number.
The two sides issued a bullish joint statement, in which they said they were
both prepared to commit 'appropriate' military forces to a peacekeeping
operation.
